library(keras)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)


data <- dataset_fashion_mnist()
## Loaded Tensorflow version 2.5.0
str(data)
## List of 2
##  $ train:List of 2

##   ..$ y: int [1:60000(1d)] 9 0 0 3 0 2 7 2 5 5 ...
##  $ test :List of 2

The dataset is already split into train and test sets. These, in turn, are split into observations and labels (x, y). We assign each into a separate variable

## Training and testing features and labels

train_images <- data$train$x
train_labels <- data$train$y

test_images <- data$test$x
test_labels <- data$test$y


train_labels[1:20]
##  [1] 9 0 0 3 0 2 7 2 5 5 0 9 5 5 7 9 1 0 6 4

We have a total of 10 classes, each represented by a digit. We store the actual class names for plotting purposes.

class_names = c('T-shirt/top',
                'Trouser',
                'Pullover',
                'Dress',
                'Coat', 
                'Sandal',
                'Shirt',
                'Sneaker',
                'Bag',
                'Ankle boot')

Let us take a look at the a sample image

image_1 <- as.data.frame(train_images[1, , ])
colnames(image_1) <- seq_len(ncol(image_1))
image_1$y <- seq_len(nrow(image_1))
image_1 <- gather(image_1, "x", "value", -y)
image_1$x <- as.integer(image_1$x)

ggplot(image_1, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "black", na.value = NA) +
  scale_y_reverse() +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank())   +
  theme(aspect.ratio = 1) +
  xlab("") +
  ylab("")

Every feature is a pixel value in the range of 0 to 255. We will normalize the features to make training easier.

train_images <- train_images / 255
test_images <- test_images  / 255

Let us take a look at the first 9 images and make sure that they have the correct corresponding labels

par(mfcol=c(3,3))
par(mar = c(0,0,1.5,0), xaxs = 'i', yaxs = 'i')

for (i in 1:9){
  img <- train_images[i, , ]
  img <- t(apply(img, 2, rev))
  image(1:28, 1:28, img, col = gray((0:255)/255), xaxt = 'n', yaxt = 'n',
        main = paste(class_names[train_labels[i] + 1]))
}

Everything looks good. We can now start building and training our model!

## Initialize a sequential model

model <- keras_model_sequential()

## Build the model

model %>%
  # First layer flattens the 2D input array into a 1D array of size 784
  layer_flatten(input_shape = c(28,28)) %>%
  # Second layer is a dense layer of size 128 and a ReLU activation function
  layer_dense(units = 128, activation = 'relu') %>%
  # Final layer is a dnese layer of size 10 (number of classes) and a softmax
  # activation function
  layer_dense(units = 10, activation = 'softmax')

## Compile the model

# configure optimzer

optimizer <- optimizer_sgd(
  learning_rate = 0.01,
  momentum = 0,
  decay = 0,
  nesterov = FALSE
)
model %>% compile(
  # Backpropagtion algorithm
  optimizer = optimizer,
  # Loss function
  loss = 'sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
  # Metric(s) used to evaluate the model while training
  metrics = c('accuracy')
)

## Train the model

# Set the number of times you want to go over the training dataset
EPOCHS <- 10

history <- model %>% 
  fit(train_images, train_labels, epochs = EPOCHS,
      validation_data = list(test_images, test_labels), verbose = 2)
plot(history, type='l', lwd= '2')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

We then evaluate our model using the test set

score <- model %>% evaluate(test_images, test_labels, verbose = 0)

cat('Test loss:', score['loss'], "\n")
## Test loss: 0.4242579
cat('Test accuracy:', score['accuracy'], "\n")
## Test accuracy: 0.8509

Using the model to make predictions

# Get probabilities for each class per sample
probs <- model %>% predict(test_images)

# Pick the class with the highest probability from the first sample
class <- which.max(probs[1, ])

# Use class names to identify the article
print(class_names[class])
## [1] "Ankle boot"

Let us visualize a few predictions

Note that the true label is the one between brackets

par(mfcol=c(5,5))
par(mar=c(0, 0, 1.5, 0), xaxs='i', yaxs='i')
for (i in 1:25) { 
  img <- test_images[i, , ]
  img <- t(apply(img, 2, rev)) 
  # subtract 1 as labels go from 0 to 9
  predicted_label <- which.max(probs[i, ]) - 1
  true_label <- test_labels[i]
  if (predicted_label == true_label) {
    color <- '#008800' 
  } else {
    color <- '#bb0000'
  }
  image(1:28, 1:28, img, col = gray((0:255)/255), xaxt = 'n', yaxt = 'n',
        main = paste0(class_names[predicted_label + 1], " (",
                      class_names[true_label + 1], ")"),
        col.main = color)
}
